# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wasm-toolchain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] The name *bytecode* stems from instruction sets that have one-byte opcodes followed by optional parameters.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Intermediate representations such as bytecode may be output by programming language implementations to ease interpretation, or it may be used to reduce hardware and operating system dependence by allowing the same code to run cross-platform, on different devices.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Bytecode may often be either directly executed on a virtual machine (a p-code machine, i.e., interpreter), or it may be further compiled into machine code for better performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Since bytecode instructions are processed by software, they may be arbitrarily complex, but are nonetheless often akin to traditional hardware instructions: virtual stack machines are the most common, but virtual register machines have been built also.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Different parts may often be stored in separate files, similar to object modules, but dynamically loaded during execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] A bytecode program may be executed by parsing and *directly* executing the instructions, one at a time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] This kind of *bytecode interpreter* is very portable.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Some systems, called dynamic translators, or *just-in-time* (JIT) compilers, translate bytecode into machine code as necessary at runtime.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] This makes the virtual machine hardware-specific but does not lose the portability of the bytecode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] For example, Java and Smalltalk code is typically stored in bytecode format, which is typically then JIT compiled to translate the bytecode to machine code before execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] This introduces a delay before a program is run, when the bytecode is compiled to native machine code, but improves execution speed considerably compared to interpreting source code directly, normally by around an order of magnitude (10x).
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Because of its performance advantage, today many language implementations execute a program in two phases, first compiling the source code into bytecode, and then passing the bytecode to the virtual machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] There are bytecode based virtual machines of this sort for Java, Raku, Python, PHP, Tcl, mawk and Forth (however, Forth is seldom compiled via bytecodes in this way, and its virtual machine is more generic instead).
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] The implementation of Perl and Ruby 1.8 instead work by walking an abstract syntax tree representation derived from the source code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] More recently, the authors of V8 and Dart have challenged the notion that intermediate bytecode is needed for fast and efficient VM implementation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Both of these language implementations currently do direct JIT compiling from source code to machine code with no bytecode intermediary.
[src:wasm-toolchain/bytecode] Compiled code can be analysed and investigated using a built-in tool for debugging the low-level bytecode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An **instruction set architecture** (**ISA**) is an abstract model that defines the programmable interface of the CPU of a computer, defining how software interacts with hardware.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] CPU) that interprets instructions described by an ISA is an implementation of that ISA.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Generally, the same ISA is used for a family of related CPU devices.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In general, an ISA defines the instructions, data types, registers, and the programming interface for managing main memory such as addressing modes, virtual memory, and memory consistency mechanisms.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The ISA also includes the input/output model of the programmable interface.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA specifies the behavior implied by machine code running on an implementation of that ISA in a fashion that does not depend on the characteristics of that implementation, providing binary compatibility between implementations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] It also enables the evolution of the microarchitectures of the implementations of that ISA, so that a newer, higher-performance implementation of an ISA can run software that runs on previous generations of implementations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] If an operating system maintains a standard and compatible application binary interface (ABI) for a particular ISA, machine code will run on future implementations of that ISA and operating system.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] However, if an ISA supports running multiple operating systems, it does not guarantee that machine code for one operating system will run on another operating system, unless the first operating system supports running machine code built for the other operating system.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can be extended by adding instructions or other capabilities, or adding support for larger addresses and data values; an implementation of the extended ISA will still be able to execute machine code for versions of the ISA without those extensions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Machine code using those extensions will only run on implementations that support those extensions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The binary compatibility that they provide makes ISAs one of the most fundamental abstractions in computing.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An instruction set architecture is distinguished from a microarchitecture, which is the set of processor design techniques used, in a particular processor, to implement the instruction set.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Processors with different microarchitectures can share a common instruction set.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For example, the Intel Pentium and the AMD Athlon implement nearly identical versions of the x86 instruction set, but they have radically different internal designs.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The concept of an *architecture*, distinct from the design of a specific machine, was developed by Fred Brooks at IBM during the design phase of System/360.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some virtual machines that support bytecode as their ISA such as Smalltalk, the Java virtual machine, and Microsoft's Common Language Runtime, implement this by translating the bytecode for commonly used code paths into native machine code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In addition, these virtual machines execute less frequently used code paths by interpretation (see: Just-in-time compilation).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Transmeta implemented the x86 instruction set atop very long instruction word (VLIW) processors in this fashion.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA may be classified in a number of different ways.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A common classification is by architectural *complexity*.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A complex instruction set computer (CISC) has many specialized instructions, some of which may only be rarely used in practical programs.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Other types include VLIW architectures, and the closely related *long instruction word* (LIW) and *explicitly parallel instruction computing* (EPIC) architectures.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] These architectures seek to exploit instruction-level parallelism with less hardware than RISC and CISC by making the compiler responsible for instruction issue and scheduling.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Architectures with even less complexity have been studied, such as the minimal instruction set computer (MISC) and one-instruction set computer (OISC).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] These are theoretically important types, but have not been commercialized.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Machine language is built up from discrete *statements* or *instructions*.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] More complex operations are built up by combining these simple instructions, which are executed sequentially, or as otherwise directed by control flow instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Processors may include elaborate instructions in their instruction set.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A single elaborate instruction does something that may require many instructions or a subroutine on other computers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Such instructions are typified by instructions that take multiple steps, control multiple functional units, or otherwise appear on a larger scale than the bulk of simple instructions implemented by the given processor.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Elaborate instructions are more common in CISC instruction sets than in RISC instruction sets, but RISC instruction sets may include them as well.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] RISC instruction sets generally do not include ALU operations with memory operands, or instructions to move large blocks of memory, but most RISC instruction sets include SIMD or vector instructions that perform the same arithmetic operation on multiple pieces of data at the same time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions have the ability of manipulating large vectors and matrices in minimal time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions allow easy parallelization of algorithms commonly involved in sound, image, and video processing.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Various SIMD implementations have been brought to market under trade names such as MMX, 3DNow!, and AltiVec.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] On traditional architectures, an instruction includes an opcode that specifies the operation to perform, such as *add contents of memory to register*—and zero or more operand specifiers, which may specify registers, memory locations, or literal data.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The operand specifiers may have addressing modes determining their meaning or may be in fixed fields.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures, which include many microcode architectures, multiple simultaneous opcodes and operands are specified in a single instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some exotic instruction sets do not have an opcode field, such as transport triggered architectures (TTA), only operand(s).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Most stack machines have "0-operand" instruction sets in which arithmetic and logical operations lack any operand specifier fields; only instructions that push operands onto the evaluation stack or that pop operands from the stack into variables have operand specifiers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or arbitrary main memory cells.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] This can be very convenient for compiling high-level languages, because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Conditional instructions often have a predicate field—a few bits that encode the specific condition to cause an operation to be performed rather than not performed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For example, a conditional branch instruction will transfer control if the condition is true, so that execution proceeds to a different part of the program, and not transfer control if the condition is false, so that execution continues sequentially.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction sets also have conditional moves, so that the move will be executed, and the data stored in the target location, if the condition is true, and not executed, and the target location not modified, if the condition is false.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Similarly, IBM z/Architecture has a conditional store instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A few instruction sets include a predicate field in every instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Having predicates on instructions is called predication, and can *include* conditional-branches, such as `bf` on the SuperH.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Many architectures have conditional branch instructions designed for controlling loops.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Typically, they update and test a register.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Instruction sets may be categorized by the maximum number of operands *explicitly* specified in instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Due to the large number of bits needed to encode the three registers of a 3-operand instruction, RISC architectures that have 16-bit instructions are invariably 2-operand designs, such as the Atmel AVR, TI MSP430, and some versions of ARM Thumb.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] RISC architectures that have 32-bit instructions are usually 3-operand designs, such as the ARM, AVR32, MIPS, Power ISA, and SPARC architectures.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] However even 3-operand RISC architectures will, at considerable cost, have Fused multiply-and-add 4-operand instructions out of necessity, due to the increased accuracy provided.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Modern examples include Power ISA and RISC-V.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Each instruction specifies some number of operands (registers, memory locations, or immediate values) *explicitly*.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some instructions give one or both operands implicitly, such as by being stored on top of the stack or in an implicit register.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] If some of the operands are given implicitly, fewer operands need be specified in the instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] When a "destination operand" explicitly specifies the destination, an additional operand must be supplied.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Consequently, the number of operands encoded in an instruction may differ from the mathematically necessary number of arguments for a logical or arithmetic operation (the arity).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Operands are either encoded in the "opcode" representation of the instruction, or else are given as values or addresses following the opcode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] While embedded instruction sets such as Thumb suffer from extremely high register pressure because they have small register sets, general-purpose RISC ISAs like MIPS and Alpha enjoy low register pressure.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] CISC ISAs like x86-64 offer low register pressure despite having smaller register sets.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] This is due to the many addressing modes and optimizations (such as sub-register addressing, memory operands in ALU instructions, absolute addressing, PC-relative addressing, and register-to-register spills) that CISC ISAs offer.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The size or length of an instruction varies widely, from as little as four bits in some microcontrollers to many hundreds of bits in some VLIW systems.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Processors used in personal computers, mainframes, and supercomputers have minimum instruction sizes between 8 and 64 bits.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The longest possible instruction on x86 is 15 bytes (120 bits).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Within an instruction set, different instructions may have different lengths.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In some architectures, notably most reduced instruction set computers (RISC), instructions are a fixed length, typically corresponding with that architecture's word size.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In other architectures, instructions have variable length, typically integral multiples of a byte or a halfword.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some, such as the ARM with *Thumb-extension* have *mixed* variable encoding, that is two fixed, usually 32-bit and 16-bit encodings, where instructions cannot be mixed freely but must be switched between on a branch (or exception boundary in ARMv8).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Fixed-length instructions are less complicated to handle than variable-length instructions for several reasons (not having to check whether an instruction straddles a cache line or virtual memory page boundary, for instance), and are therefore somewhat easier to optimize for speed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In early 1960s computers, main memory was expensive and very limited, even on mainframes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Minimizing the size of a program to make sure it would fit in the limited memory was often central.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Thus the size of the instructions needed to perform a particular task, the *code density*, was an important characteristic of any instruction set.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] It remained important on the initially-tiny memories of minicomputers and then microprocessors.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Density remains important today, for smartphone applications, applications downloaded into browsers over slow Internet connections, and in ROMs for embedded applications.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A more general advantage of increased density is improved effectiveness of caches and instruction prefetch.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Computers with high code density often have complex instructions for procedure entry, parameterized returns, loops, etc.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] (therefore retroactively named *Complex Instruction Set Computers*, CISC).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] However, more typical, or frequent, "CISC" instructions merely combine a basic ALU operation, such as "add", with the access of one or more operands in memory (using addressing modes such as direct, indirect, indexed, etc.).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Certain architectures may allow two or three operands (including the result) directly in memory or may be able to perform functions such as automatic pointer increment, etc.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Software-implemented instruction sets may have even more complex and powerful instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Certain embedded RISC ISAs like Thumb and AVR32 typically exhibit very high density owing to a technique called code compression.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] This technique packs two 16-bit instructions into one 32-bit word, which is then unpacked at the decode stage and executed as two instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Minimal instruction set computers (MISC) are commonly a form of stack machine, where there are few separate instructions (8–32), so that multiple instructions can be fit into a single machine word.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] These types of cores often take little silicon to implement, so they can be easily realized in an FPGA (field-programmable gate array) or in a multi-core form.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The code density of MISC is similar to the code density of RISC; the increased instruction density is offset by requiring more of the primitive instructions to do a task.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] There has been research into executable compression as a mechanism for improving code density.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The mathematics of Kolmogorov complexity describes the challenges and limits of this.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In practice, code density is also dependent on the compiler.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Most optimizing compilers have options that control whether to optimize code generation for execution speed or for code density.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For instance GCC has the option `-Os` to optimize for small machine code size, and `-O3` to optimize for execution speed at the cost of larger machine code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The instructions constituting a program are rarely specified using their internal, numeric form (machine code); they may be specified by programmers using an assembly language or, more commonly, may be generated from high-level programming languages by compilers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The design of instruction sets is a complex issue.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] There were two stages in history for the microprocessor.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The first was the CISC (complex instruction set computer), which had many different instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] In the 1970s, however, places like IBM did research and found that many instructions in the set could be eliminated.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The result was the RISC (reduced instruction set computer), an architecture that uses a smaller set of instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A simpler instruction set may offer the potential for higher speeds, reduced processor size, and reduced power consumption.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] However, a more complex set may optimize common operations, improve memory and cache efficiency, or simplify programming.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction set designers reserve one or more opcodes for some kind of system call or software interrupt.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For example, MOS Technology 6502 uses 00H, Zilog Z80 uses the eight codes C7,CF,D7,DF,E7,EF,F7,FFH while Motorola 68000 use codes in the range 4E40H-4E4FH.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Fast virtual machines are much easier to implement if an instruction set meets the Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The NOP slide used in immunity-aware programming is much easier to implement if the "unprogrammed" state of the memory is interpreted as a NOP.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] On systems with multiple processors, non-blocking synchronization algorithms are much easier to implement if the instruction set includes support for something such as "fetch-and-add", "load-link/store-conditional" (LL/SC), or "atomic compare-and-swap".
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] A given instruction set can be implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] All ways of implementing a particular instruction set provide the same programming model, and all implementations of that instruction set are able to run the same executables.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The various ways of implementing an instruction set give different tradeoffs between cost, performance, power consumption, size, etc.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] When designing the microarchitecture of a processor, engineers use blocks of "hard-wired" electronic circuitry (often designed separately) such as adders, multiplexers, counters, registers, ALUs, etc.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some kind of register transfer language is then often used to describe the decoding and sequencing of each instruction of an ISA using this physical microarchitecture.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Other designs employ microcode routines or tables (or both) to do this, using ROMs or writable RAMs (writable control store), PLAs, or both.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Some microcoded CPU designs with a writable control store use it to allow the instruction set to be changed (for example, the Rekursiv processor and the Imsys Cjip).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] CPUs designed for reconfigurable computing may use field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can also be emulated in software by an interpreter.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Naturally, due to the interpretation overhead, this is slower than directly running programs on the emulated hardware, unless the hardware running the emulator is an order of magnitude faster.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Today, it is common practice for vendors of new ISAs or microarchitectures to make software emulators available to software developers before the hardware implementation is ready.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] Often the details of the implementation have a strong influence on the particular instructions selected for the instruction set.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For example, many implementations of the instruction pipeline only allow a single memory load or memory store per instruction, leading to a load–store architecture (RISC).
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For another example, some early ways of implementing the instruction pipeline led to a delay slot.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] The demands of high-speed digital signal processing have pushed in the opposite direction—forcing instructions to be implemented in a particular way.
[src:wasm-toolchain/instruction-set-architecture] For example, to perform digital filters fast enough, the MAC instruction in a typical digital signal processor (DSP) must use a kind of Harvard architecture that can fetch an instruction and two data words simultaneously, and it requires a single-cycle multiply–accumulate multiplier.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:wasm-toolchain/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In computer science, computer engineering and programming language implementations, a **stack machine** is a computer processor or a process virtual machine in which the primary interaction is moving short-lived temporary values to and from a push-down stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In the case of a hardware processor, a hardware stack is used.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The use of a stack significantly reduces the required number of processor registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines extend push-down automata with additional load/store operations or multiple stacks and hence are Turing-complete.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Most or all stack machine instructions assume that operands will be from the stack, and results placed in the stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The stack easily holds more than two inputs or more than one result, so a rich set of operations can be computed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In stack machine code (sometimes called p-code), instructions will frequently have only an opcode commanding an operation, with no additional fields identifying a constant, register or memory cell, known as a **zero address format**.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A computer that operates in such a way that the majority of its instructions do not include explicit addresses is said to utilize zero-address instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This greatly simplifies instruction decoding.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Branches, load immediates, and load/store instructions require an argument field, but stack machines often arrange that the frequent cases of these still fit together with the opcode into a compact group of bits.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The selection of operands from prior results is done implicitly by ordering the instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some stack machine instruction sets are intended for interpretive execution of a virtual machine, rather than driving hardware directly.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Integer constant operands are pushed by `Push` or `Load Immediate` instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Memory is often accessed by separate `Load` or `Store` instructions containing a memory address or calculating the address from values in the stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] All practical stack machines have variants of the load–store opcodes for accessing local variables and formal parameters without explicit address calculations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This can be by offsets from the current top-of-stack address, or by offsets from a stable frame-base register.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or main memory cells.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This can be very convenient for executing high-level languages because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] For example, consider the expression *A**(*B*−*C*)+(*D*+*E*), written in reverse Polish notation as *A* *B* *C* − * *D* *E* + +.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The arithmetic operations "subtract", "multiply", and "add" act on the two topmost operands of the stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The computer takes both operands from the topmost (most recent) values of the stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The computer replaces those two values with the calculated difference, sum, or product.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In other words the instruction's operands are "popped" off the stack, and its result(s) are then "pushed" back onto the stack, ready for the next instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines may have their expression stack and their call-return stack separated or as one integrated structure.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] If they are separated, the instructions of the stack machine can be pipelined with fewer interactions and less design complexity, so it will usually run faster.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Optimisation of compiled stack code is quite possible.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Back-end optimisation of compiler output has been demonstrated to significantly improve code, and potentially performance, whilst global optimisation within the compiler itself achieves further gains.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some stack machines have a stack of limited size, implemented as a register file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A large register file uses a lot of transistors and hence this method is only suitable for small systems.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A few machines have both an expression stack in memory and a separate register stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In this case, software, or an interrupt may move data between them.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some machines have a stack of unlimited size, implemented as an array in RAM, which is cached by some number of "top of stack" address registers to reduce memory access.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Except for explicit "load from memory" instructions, the order of operand usage is identical with the order of the operands in the data stack, so excellent prefetching can be accomplished easily.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It compiles to `Load X`; `Load 1`; `Add`.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The next step up from this is a stack machine or interpreter with a single top-of-stack register.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] for a total of 3 data cache references, worst-case.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Generally, interpreters don't track emptiness, because they don't have to—anything below the stack pointer is a non-empty value, and the TOS cache register is always kept hot.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Typical Java interpreters do not buffer the top-of-stack this way, however, because the program and stack have a mix of short and wide data values.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] If the hardwired stack machine has 2 or more top-stack registers, or a register file, then all memory access is avoided in this example and there is only 1 data cache cycle.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Description of such a method requiring only two values at a time to be held in registers, with a limited set of pre-defined operands that were able to be extended by definition of further operands, functions and subroutines, was first provided at conference by Robert S.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Pure stack machines are quite inefficient for procedures which access multiple fields from the same object.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The stack machine code must reload the object pointer for each pointer+offset calculation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A common fix for this is to add some register-machine features to the stack machine: a visible register file dedicated to holding addresses, and register-style instructions for doing loads and simple address calculations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is uncommon to have the registers be fully general purpose, because then there is no strong reason to have an expression stack and postfix instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Another common hybrid is to start with a register machine architecture, and add another memory address mode which emulates the push or pop operations of stack machines: "memaddress = reg; reg += instr.displ".
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This was first used in DEC's PDP-11 minicomputer.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This feature was carried forward in VAX computers and in Motorola 6809 and 68000 series microprocessors.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This allowed the use of simpler stack methods in early compilers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It also efficiently supported virtual machines using stack interpreters or threaded code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] However, this feature did not help the register machine's own code to become as compact as pure stack machine code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Also, the execution speed was less than when compiling well to the register architecture.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is faster to change the top-of-stack pointer only occasionally (once per call or return) rather than constantly stepping it up and down throughout each program statement, and it is even faster to avoid memory references entirely.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] More recently, so-called second-generation stack machines have adopted a dedicated collection of registers to serve as address registers, off-loading the task of memory addressing from the data stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] For example, MuP21 relies on a register called "A", while the more recent GreenArrays processors relies on two registers: A and B.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The Intel x86 family of microprocessors have a register-style (accumulator) instruction set for most operations, but use stack instructions for its x87, Intel 8087 floating point arithmetic, dating back to the iAPX87 (8087) coprocessor for the 8086 and 8088.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] That is, there are no programmer-accessible floating point registers, but only an 80-bit wide, 8-level deep stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The x87 relies heavily on the x86 CPU for assistance in performing its operations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Most current computers (of any instruction set style) and most compilers use a large call-return stack in memory to organize the short-lived local variables and return links for all currently active procedures or functions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Each nested call creates a new **stack frame** in memory, which persists until that call completes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This call-return stack may be entirely managed by the hardware via specialized address registers and special address modes in the instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Or it may be merely a set of conventions followed by the compilers, using generic registers and register+offset address modes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Since this technique is now nearly universal, even on register machines, it is not helpful to refer to all these machines as stack machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] That term is commonly reserved for machines which also use an expression stack and stack-only arithmetic instructions to evaluate the pieces of a single statement.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Computers commonly provide direct, efficient access to the program's global variables and to the local variables of only the current innermost procedure or function, the topmost stack frame.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] "Up level" addressing of the contents of callers' stack frames is usually not needed and not supported as directly by the hardware.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] If needed, compilers support this by passing in frame pointers as additional, hidden parameters.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some Burroughs stack machines do support up-level refs directly in the hardware, with specialized address modes and a special "display" register file holding the frame addresses of all outer scopes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Currently, only MCST Elbrus has done this in hardware.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] When Niklaus Wirth developed the first Pascal compiler for the CDC 6000 series, he found that it was faster overall to pass in the frame pointers as a chain, rather than constantly updating complete arrays of frame pointers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This software method also adds no overhead for common languages like C which lack up-level refs.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The same Burroughs machines also supported nesting of tasks or threads.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The task and its creator share the stack frames that existed at the time of task creation, but not the creator's subsequent frames nor the task's own frames.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This was supported by a cactus stack, whose layout diagram resembled the trunk and arms of a Saguaro cactus.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Each task had its own memory segment holding its stack and the frames that it owns.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The base of this stack is linked to the middle of its creator's stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In machines with a conventional flat address space, the creator stack and task stacks would be separate heap objects in one heap.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In some programming languages, the outer-scope data environments are not always nested in time.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] These languages organize their procedure "activation records" as separate heap objects rather than as stack frames appended to a linear stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In simple languages like Forth that lack local variables and naming of parameters, stack frames would contain nothing more than return branch addresses and frame management overhead.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] So their return stack holds bare return addresses rather than frames.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The return stack is separate from the data value stack, to improve the flow of call setup and returns.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines are often compared to register machines, which hold values in an array of registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Register machines may store stack-like structures in this array, but a register machine has instructions which circumvent the stack interface.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Register machines routinely outperform stack machines, and stack machines have remained a niche player in hardware systems.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] But stack machines are often used in implementing virtual machines because of their simplicity and ease of implementation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines have higher code density.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In contrast to common stack machine instructions which can easily fit in 6 bits or less, register machines require two or three register-number fields per ALU instruction to select operands; the densest register machines average about 16 bits per instruction plus the operands.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Register machines also use a wider offset field for load-store opcodes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A stack machine's compact code naturally fits more instructions in cache, and therefore could achieve better cache efficiency, reducing memory costs or permitting faster memory systems for a given cost.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In addition, most stack-machine instructions are very simple, made from only one opcode field or one operand field.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Thus, stack-machines require very little electronic resources to decode each instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A program has to execute more instructions when compiled to a stack machine than when compiled to a register machine or memory-to-memory machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Every variable load or constant requires its own separate Load instruction, instead of being bundled within the instruction which uses that value.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The separated instructions may be simple and faster running, but the total instruction count is still higher.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Most register interpreters specify their registers by number.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] But a host machine's registers can't be accessed in an indexed array, so a memory array is allotted for virtual registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Therefore, the instructions of a register interpreter must use memory for passing generated data to the next instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This forces register interpreters to be much slower on microprocessors made with a fine process rule (i.e. faster transistors without improving circuit speeds, such as the Haswell x86).
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] These require several clocks for memory access, but only one clock for register access.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This may preserve such registers and cache for use in non-flow computation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some in the industry believe that stack machines execute more data cache cycles for temporary values and local variables than do register machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] On stack machines, temporary values often get spilled into memory, whereas on machines with many registers these temps usually remain in registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] (However, these values often need to be spilled into "activation frames" at the end of a procedure's definition, basic block, or at the very least, into a memory buffer during interrupt processing).
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Values spilled to memory add more cache cycles.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This spilling effect depends on the number of hidden registers used to buffer top-of-stack values, upon the frequency of nested procedure calls, and upon host computer interrupt processing rates.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] On register machines using optimizing compilers, it is very common for the most-used local variables to remain in registers rather than in stack frame memory cells.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This eliminates most data cache cycles for reading and writing those values.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The development of "stack scheduling" for performing live-variable analysis, and thus retaining key variables on the stack for extended periods, helps this concern.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] On the other hand, register machines must spill many of their registers to memory across nested procedure calls.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The decision of which registers to spill, and when, is made statically at compile time rather than on the dynamic depth of the calls.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This can lead to more data cache traffic than in an advanced stack machine implementation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In register machines, a common subexpression (a subexpression which is used multiple times with the same result value) can be evaluated just once and its result saved in a fast register.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The subsequent reuses have no time or code cost, just a register reference.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This optimization speeds simple expressions (for example, loading variable X or pointer P) as well as less-common complex expressions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] With stack machines, in contrast, results can be stored in one of two ways.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Firstly, results can be stored using a temporary variable in memory.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Storing and subsequent retrievals cost additional instructions and additional data cache cycles.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Doing this is only a win if the subexpression computation costs more in time than fetching from memory, which in most stack CPUs, almost always is the case.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is never worthwhile for simple variables and pointer fetches, because those already have the same cost of one data cache cycle per access.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is only marginally worthwhile for expressions such as `X+1`.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] These simpler expressions make up the majority of redundant, optimizable expressions in programs written in languages other than concatenative languages.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] An optimizing compiler can only win on redundancies that the programmer could have avoided in the source code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The second way leaves a computed value on the data stack, duplicating it as needed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This uses operations to copy stack entries.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The stack must be depth shallow enough for the CPU's available copy instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Hand-written stack code often uses this approach, and achieves speeds like general-purpose register machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Unfortunately, algorithms for optimal "stack scheduling" are not in wide use by programming languages.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In modern machines, the time to fetch a variable from the data cache is often several times longer than the time needed for basic ALU operations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] A program runs faster without stalls if its memory loads can be started several cycles before the instruction that needs that variable.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Complex machines can do this with a deep pipeline and "out-of-order execution" that examines and runs many instructions at once.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Register machines can even do this with much simpler "in-order" hardware, a shallow pipeline, and slightly smarter compilers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The load step becomes a separate instruction, and that instruction is statically scheduled much earlier in the code sequence.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The compiler puts independent steps in between.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Scheduling memory accesses requires explicit, spare registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is not possible on stack machines without exposing some aspect of the micro-architecture to the programmer.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] For the expression A B −, B must be evaluated and pushed immediately prior to the Minus step.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Without stack permutation or hardware multithreading, relatively little useful code can be put in between while waiting for the Load B to finish.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Today's increasingly parallel computational loads suggests, however, this might not be the disadvantage it's been made out to be in the past.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines can omit the operand fetching stage of a register machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] For example, in the Java Optimized Processor (JOP) microprocessor the top 2 operands of stack directly enter a data forwarding circuit that is faster than the register file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The Tomasulo algorithm finds instruction-level parallelism by issuing instructions as their data becomes available.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Conceptually, the addresses of positions in a stack are no different than the register indexes of a register file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This view permits the out-of-order execution of the Tomasulo algorithm to be used with stack machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Out-of-order execution in stack machines seems to reduce or avoid many theoretical and practical difficulties.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The cited research shows that such a stack machine can exploit instruction-level parallelism, and the resulting hardware must cache data for the instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Such machines effectively bypass most memory accesses to the stack.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The result achieves throughput (instructions per clock) comparable to load–store architecture machines, with much higher code densities (because operand addresses are implicit).
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] One issue brought up in the research was that it takes about 1.88 stack-machine instructions to do the work of one instruction on a load-store architecture machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Competitive out-of-order stack machines therefore require about twice as many electronic resources to track instructions ("issue stations").
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This might be compensated by savings in instruction cache and memory and instruction decoding circuits.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some simple stack machines have a chip design which is fully customized all the way down to the level of individual registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The top of stack address register and the N top of stack data buffers are built from separate individual register circuits, with separate adders and ad hoc connections.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] However, most stack machines are built from larger circuit components where the N data buffers are stored together within a register file and share read/write buses.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The decoded stack instructions are mapped into one or more sequential actions on that hidden register file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Loads and ALU ops act on a few topmost registers, and implicit spills and fills act on the bottommost registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The decoder allows the instruction stream to be compact.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] But if the code stream instead had explicit register-select fields which directly manipulated the underlying register file, the compiler could make better use of all registers and the program would run faster.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Microprogrammed stack machines are an example of this.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The inner microcode engine is some kind of RISC-like register machine or a VLIW-like machine using multiple register files.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] When controlled directly by task-specific microcode, that engine gets much more work completed per cycle than when controlled indirectly by equivalent stack code for that same task.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The object code translators that translated code for the HP 3000 and Tandem NonStop stack machines to code for the register-based RISC replacements for those machines are another example.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] They translated stack code sequences into equivalent sequences of RISC code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Minor "local" optimizations removed much of the overhead of a stack architecture.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Spare registers were used to factor out repeated address calculations.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The translated code still retained plenty of emulation overhead from the mismatch between original and target machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Despite that burden, the cycle efficiency of the translated code matched the cycle efficiency of the original stack code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] And when the source code was recompiled directly to the register machine via optimizing compilers, the efficiency doubled.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This shows that the stack architecture and its non-optimizing compilers were wasting over half of the power of the underlying hardware.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Register files are good tools for computing because they have high bandwidth and very low latency, compared to memory references via data caches.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In a simple machine, the register file allows reading two independent registers and writing of a third, all in one ALU cycle with one-cycle or less latency.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Whereas the corresponding data cache can start only one read or one write (not both) per cycle, and the read typically has a latency of two ALU cycles.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] That's one third of the throughput at twice the pipeline delay.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In a complex machine like Athlon that completes two or more instructions per cycle, the register file allows reading of four or more independent registers and writing of two others, all in one ALU cycle with one-cycle latency.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Whereas the corresponding dual-ported data cache can start only two reads or writes per cycle, with multiple cycles of latency.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Again, that's one third of the throughput of registers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] It is very expensive to build a cache with additional ports.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Since a stack is a component of most software programs, even when the software used is not strictly a stack machine, a hardware stack machine might more closely mimic the inner workings of its programs.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Processor registers have a high thermal cost, and a stack machine might claim higher energy efficiency.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Responding to an interrupt involves saving the registers to a stack, and then branching to the interrupt handler code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Often stack machines respond more quickly to interrupts, because most parameters are already on a stack and there is no need to push them there.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Some register machines deal with this by having multiple register files that can be instantly swapped but this increases costs and slows down the register file.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Interpreters for virtual stack machines are easier to build than interpreters for register machines; the logic for handling memory address modes is in just one place rather than repeated in many instructions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Stack machines also tend to have fewer variations of an opcode; one generalized opcode will handle both frequent cases and obscure corner cases of memory references or function call setup.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Interpreters for virtual stack machines are often slower than interpreters for other styles of virtual machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This slowdown is worst when running on host machines with deep execution pipelines, such as current x86 chips.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] In some interpreters, the interpreter must execute a N-way switch jump to decode the next opcode and branch to its steps for that particular opcode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Another method for selecting opcodes is threaded code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] The host machine's prefetch mechanisms are unable to predict and fetch the target of that indexed or indirect jump.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] So the host machine's execution pipeline must restart each time the hosted interpreter decodes another virtual instruction.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This happens more often for virtual stack machines than for other styles of virtual machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] One example is the Java programming language.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Its canonical virtual machine is specified as an 8-bit stack machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] However, the Dalvik virtual machine for Java used on Android smartphones is a 16-bit virtual-register machine—a choice made for efficiency reasons.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Arithmetic instructions directly fetch or store local variables via 4-bit (or larger) instruction fields.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Similarly version 5.0 of Lua replaced its virtual stack machine with a faster virtual register machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] Since Java virtual machine became popular, microprocessors have employed advanced branch predictors for indirect jumps.
[src:wasm-toolchain/stack-machine] This advance avoids most of pipeline restarts from N-way jumps and eliminates much of the instruction count costs that affect stack interpreters.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly (abbreviated *Wasm*) is a binary instruction format for a stack-based virtual machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] Wasm is designed as a portable compilation target for programming languages, enabling deployment on the web for client and server applications.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] The Wasm stack machine is designed to be encoded in a size- and load-time-efficient binary format.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly aims to execute at native speed by taking advantage of common hardware capabilities available on a wide range of platforms.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly describes a memory-safe, sandboxed execution environment that may even be implemented inside existing JavaScript virtual machines.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] When embedded in the web, WebAssembly will enforce the same-origin and permissions security policies of the browser.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly is designed to be pretty-printed in a textual format for debugging, testing, experimenting, optimizing, learning, teaching, and writing programs by hand.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] The textual format will be used when viewing the source of Wasm modules on the web.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly is designed to maintain the versionless, feature-tested, and backwards-compatible nature of the web.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly modules will be able to call into and out of the JavaScript context and access browser functionality through the same Web APIs accessible from JavaScript.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly-org] WebAssembly also supports non-web embeddings.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:wasm-toolchain/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
